      "content": "The core economic theory you mention is often discussed under the concept of substitution or income effects, which posit that benefits reduce the incentive to earn more. However, applying this theory to real-world policy is where the difficulty lies, as human behavior is not always purely rational. Furthermore, programs are usually not designed to replace all income, and often offer benefits that support activities other than solely wage-earning, like education or caregiving.",
